explanation:
Required symbols and why they matter for unreachable-code analysis:

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - This macro/function computes impl from the table and token. Its expansion determines whether impl can be NULL, cause a program exit/longjmp, or otherwise make subsequent code unreachable. You must see its definition to know if the assignment or dereference is conditional/always succeeds.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken
  - The static graph shows OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET may call this helper. Its behavior (e.g., returning an invalid index, causing an error, or terminating) affects whether the code that follows is reachable.

- OS_impl_condvar_table
  - The table argument to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its type/layout or special semantics could make the lookup a no-op or cause an early return/abort, which would affect reachability of later statements.

- OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t
  - The structure type of impl. Needed to know whether the impl pointer can be NULL or if impl->mut access has side effects. Also to confirm the presence/offset of the mut member.

- (impl->mut) member / pthread_mutex_t type
  - The exact type of mut (typically pthread_mutex_t) is required to confirm the call to pthread_mutex_unlock(&impl->mut) is well-typed and whether taking its address could have undefined behavior that makes code unreachable.

- pthread_mutex_unlock
  - Its prototype and documented return semantics determine whether the function can return non-zero (so the if branch can be taken) or whether it never returns (e.g., replaced by a macro that aborts). This directly decides if either return (OS_ERROR or OS_SUCCESS) is unreachable.

- OS_ERROR and OS_SUCCESS
  - The values (macros/enums) returned determine whether the two return statements produce distinct results. If they are identical or one is unreachable by construction, that affects whether any return statement is unreachable code.

- OS_object_token_t
  - The token type is used in the lookup (*token). Its definition may impose constraints (e.g., special encoding or invalid values) that influence OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET behavior and thus reachability.

Collecting these symbols allows a precise determination whether either branch/return in OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl is impossible to reach (i.e., unreachable code) under the actual definitions and semantics used in the project.
